{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01CjhMmY4KyGhykGbqFNcAig","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01GBUGb9PNh1HB29XzPuSYm7","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels so that the summary can attribute statements to specific attendees.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The real failure is that speaker labels are lost or not parsed correctly from the speech-to-text API response. A mock API using a documented response format would hide failures if: (1) the real API's diarization format differs from the mock, (2) the real API doesn't support speaker labels in the way expected, or (3) the parsing code handles the documented format but fails on the actual format. Testing with the real speech-to-text API is required to ensure the code correctly handles the actual response structure and preserves labels end-to-end.","test_description":"Call the real speech-to-text API with a multi-speaker audio sample or transcript segment where multiple distinct speakers make statements. Verify that the API response includes speaker labels (e.g., diarization enabled). Confirm that these labels are correctly parsed and forwarded through the pipeline to the LLM input without loss or corruption. Validate that speaker attribution is present for each statement reaching the summarizer.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.35,"System":0.48,"Agentic":0.12,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The structured summary contains at least one action item for every attendee who was assigned a task during the meeting.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The failure here is that the real LLM does not correctly extract or attribute action items. Mocking the LLM to return a perfect summary would hide the actual failure: the LLM either misses action items, misattributes them 